[src:bill-joyce-baseball/abner-dalrymple] Dalrymple started his major league career in 1878 with the National League's Milwaukee Grays, and that season, he had a career-high .354 batting average.
[src:bill-joyce-baseball/abner-dalrymple] He spent the next eight seasons with the Chicago White Stockings, for whom he starred as the leadoff hitter on five NL pennant winners.
[src:bill-joyce-baseball/abner-dalrymple] In 1880, Dalrymple led the league in hits (126) and runs scored (91).
[src:bill-joyce-baseball/abner-dalrymple] In 1881, he became the first batter known to be given an intentional walk with the bases loaded.
[src:bill-joyce-baseball/abner-dalrymple] He hit four doubles in a game in 1883, which still ties him for the major league record.
[src:bill-joyce-baseball/abner-dalrymple] In 1884, aided by the short right field fence at his home park, Dalrymple hit a career-high 22 home runs and moved into sixth place on the all-time home run list.
[src:bill-joyce-baseball/abner-dalrymple] On the strength of 11 home runs for the 1885 champions, he moved up one place.
[src:bill-joyce-baseball/abner-dalrymple] For the remainder of his career, he hit only six home runs.
[src:bill-joyce-baseball/abner-dalrymple] His hitting declined in 1886, and his major league career ended five years later.
[src:bill-joyce-baseball/abner-dalrymple] Dalrymple died in Warren, Illinois at age 81.
[src:bill-joyce-baseball/abner-dalrymple] Dalrymple is sometimes cited as one of only three players in MLB history to win a batting title during his rookie season, a feat which he accomplished in 1878.
[src:bill-joyce-baseball/bill-joyce-baseball] Joyce was born on September 22, 1867, to Irish immigrants in St.
[src:bill-joyce-baseball/bill-joyce-baseball] He worked in a rolling mill before beginning his minor league career in the Texas League in 1887.
[src:bill-joyce-baseball/bill-joyce-baseball] He continued in the Texas League in 1888 and 1889.
[src:bill-joyce-baseball/bill-joyce-baseball] Louis Browns player-manager Charlie Comiskey at a December 1889 exhibition game, leading Comiskey to recommend that Players' League founder John Montgomery Ward hire Joyce for his Brooklyn Ward's Wonders club.
[src:bill-joyce-baseball/bill-joyce-baseball] In the Players' League's lone season, Joyce led the league in walks, with 123 in 133 games.
[src:bill-joyce-baseball/bill-joyce-baseball] In 1891, he reached base in 64 consecutive games, a major league record not bettered until 1941.
[src:bill-joyce-baseball/bill-joyce-baseball] After the Players' League folded, Joyce signed with the Boston Reds of the American Association for that league's final year, 1891.
[src:bill-joyce-baseball/bill-joyce-baseball] He then joined Monte Ward's Brooklyn Grooms for the 1892 season.
[src:bill-joyce-baseball/bill-joyce-baseball] After an offseason trade, he held out against the Washington Senators for the entire 1893 season.
[src:bill-joyce-baseball/bill-joyce-baseball] He returned in 1894 and was named team captain.
[src:bill-joyce-baseball/bill-joyce-baseball] Joyce became a leading slugger for the next several seasons; between 1894 and 1898, he led the majors in home runs (60), was fifth in slugging percentage (.497), and seventh in on-base percentage (.444).
[src:bill-joyce-baseball/bill-joyce-baseball] He tied for the National League lead in home runs in 1896 (with Ed Delahanty) while playing for Washington and New York, and finished second three other times.
[src:bill-joyce-baseball/bill-joyce-baseball] He holds the record with four triples in one game, which he accomplished in 1897 (tying George Strief's 1885 record).
[src:bill-joyce-baseball/bill-joyce-baseball] Joyce served as player-manager with New York.
[src:bill-joyce-baseball/bill-joyce-baseball] Despite generally being popular with other players, Joyce gradually lost favor with Giants owner Andrew Freedman and was not brought back after the 1898 season.
[src:bill-joyce-baseball/bill-joyce-baseball] Joyce also developed a reputation as a frequent and vociferous critic of umpire calls, earning numerous fines for arguing.
[src:bill-joyce-baseball/bill-joyce-baseball] In 906 games over eight seasons, Joyce posted a .293 batting average (971-for-3,310) with 822 runs, 153 doubles, 106 triples, 70 home runs, 609 RBI, 266 stolen bases, 721 bases on balls, .435 on-base percentage and .467 slugging percentage.
[src:bill-joyce-baseball/bill-joyce-baseball] His walk rate of 17.3% was the second-highest in major league history between 1871 and 1920, the advent of the live-ball era.
[src:bill-joyce-baseball/bill-joyce-baseball] After retiring in December 1899, Joyce held many jobs, including saloonkeeper, minor league owner and manager, professional baseball scout, security guard, and municipal smoke inspector.
